Introduction {#s1}
============

Iron deficiency anemia (IDA) is one of the commonest nutritional deficiencies globally, with young children, women of childbearing age and pregnant women at highest risk [@pone.0004030-Centres1]. Adequate iron stores are important for normal childhood growth and development [@pone.0004030-Centres1] and IDA may impair cognitive development [@pone.0004030-Lozoff1], [@pone.0004030-McCall1]. Nutritional deficiencies are particularly prevalent in resettled pediatric refugees, who often have significant co-morbidities (including acute chronic infection and/or hemoglobinopathies) which may exacerbate IDA [@pone.0004030-McGillvray1]. Hepcidin, a type II acute phase peptide, plays a central role in the regulation of iron homeostasis [@pone.0004030-Ganz1], [@pone.0004030-Kemna1].

